PENGUIN DIE-OFF, ZOO - AUSTRALIA (QUEENSLAND)
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Wed 14 Mar 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: News.com.au [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,21377746-2,00.html>

Gold Coast attraction Sea World has lost one of its prized
attractions with the deaths of 25 of its 37 fairy penguins.
The birds started dying on Thursday [8 Mar 2007], leading to fears
they may have been infected with avian bird flu. This was ruled out
last night [Tue 13 Mar 2007] by the newly established Biosecurity
Queensland, which has been testing the birds.
Sea World's manager of marine sciences, Steve McCourt, last night
[Tue 13 Mar 2007] said he suspected the deaths were caused by a load
of contaminated gravel that had been placed in the bird's enclosure
as part of 3-monthly maintenance.
"All the staff here are absolutely devastated about this," Mr McCourt
said. We think there is some sort of toxin in the gravel."
Sea World 1st took samples to a private laboratory and then called in
Biosecurity, which worked on Monday night [12 Mar 2007] to clear up
fears of bird flu.
Mr McCourt declined to say where Sea World obtained the gravel.
Biosecurity Queensland principal veterinary officer, Ian Douglas,
said tests for bird flu were negative.
"It's a bit too early to speculate what's happened," he said. "But in
the veterinary world, it's not unusual to get a large number of
animals affected at the one time. If one is exposed to a toxin then
often they all are, and you get large crashes."
The display has been closed and the remaining penguins have been quarantined.
Mr McCourt said the 12 surviving birds were of mixed sex and, with
the species being a prolific breeder, this would be sufficient for
numbers to recover. "We've had the penguins here for over 20 years
and never had any issues before," he said. "Our primary focus is on
the remaining birds ... the enclosure has been completely stripped
and we're confident the situation has passed."
Dr Douglas said he had never seen a similar occurrence with
penguins. He said it might take 2 or more weeks to determine what
killed the birds.
Sea World's original saltwater public swimming pool was turned into
the Penguins on Parade exhibit about 20 years ago.
[Byline: Brian Williams]
