[2]
Date: Thu15 Mar 2007
From: Ian Douglas <Ian.Douglas@dpi.qld.gov.au>
Source: Official release [edited]

There has been considerable local media coverage of an episode
involving the deaths of 25 of 37 Australian little penguins at a
Queensland marine park.
These deaths commenced on 8 Mar 2007. The remaining 12 penguins are
reported to be recovering and no deaths have occurred during the last 4 days.
Biosecurity Queensland, an arm of the Queensland Department of
Primary Industries and Fisheries, is [collaborating] with the
veterinary staff at the park and private pathologists to determine
the cause of the mortality.
Highly pathogenic avian influenza was routinely excluded by PCR
[polymerase chain reaction] on 12 March 2007.
There are no reports of more widespread involvement and no immediate
indication that an infectious disease process is involved. A toxic
cause would seem to be most probable at this stage.
A range of diagnostic approaches will be used including
histopathology, culture, and toxicological studies.
The penguins are well contained and are unlikely to present any risk
to other birds or to people.
--
Rick Webster
Deputy Chief Veterinary Officer
Queensland Department of Primary Industries and Fisheries
<Rick.Webster@dpi.qld.gov.au>
--
Ian Douglas
<Ian.Douglas@dpi.qld.gov.au>
[A photo of a fairy penguin may be seen at:
<http://www.windgrove.com/mtblogpix/fairy%20penguin.jpg>
The fairy penquin is the smallest penguin, only about 16 inches (41
cm.) tall and about 2 pounds (0.9 kg.) in weight, and is found only
in the southern hemisphere. Its scientific name is _Eudyptula minor_.
Eudyptula is Greek for 'good diver'. They are blue or slate blue-grey
with a white stripe around the wings.
We are saddened by the loss of these birds. We look forward to
knowing what has killed them. There is not enough information here
to speculate on what toxin may have been in the gravel. - Mod.TG]
